(colour:#62ab26)[[No style image]].(display:"planner")(display:"Nigeria")Here is a collection of four systems where money and technology can be barriers that inhibit communities from engaginging in an equitable manner. Each story explores each system and its levels of authorship. Which system will you visit first? Will you start with a story on [[ToGoodToGo]], strategies in authorship methods for [[Effective workflow of architects]], [[informal housing]] in Lagos, or [[the money bail system in the United States of America?|The Money Bail System in the United States of America]] [[Credits]] Hey! Seems like you're hungry. But we gotta save up some money so we can go out to Cancun after finals! Did you remember to bring your [[phone]] to class today ([[or not]])? <img src="https://apply-gsapp-columbia-edu.cdn.technolutions.net/www/images/Avery%20Hall_facade%20daytime_by%20Ofer%20Wolberger.jpg" width="1000" height="667">[[Discover the system |purpose]] [[Experience the system |experience start]] [[Main Menu]] [[Credits]] The inceptive purpose of the money bail system in the United States of America was to make sure people show up to court. Research has since shown that money bail is not needed to achieve this. The actual effect is that this system perpetuates the incarceration of people based on how much money they have. While there are some states that have bail reforms, the money bail system is the reality in the majority of the United States of America. After a person is arrested, they can either pay (an intentionally large amount of money) for cash bail to leave jail or they must stay in jail. If they have the money to pay cash bail, they can decide if they want to stay in jail or pay that large amount of money to leave. If they do not have the money to pay cash bail, they either must stay in jail while they wait for their trial (which can be years), or they can pay a smaller amount of money to a bail bonds company (a fee they would not get back even if they show up to trial and are not charged), or they can plead guilty and give up the right to a trial. These choices are influenced by if a family can afford cash bail or to pay a bail bondsman. If the family pays bail or a bail bondsman, a poor family may be significantly impacted by paying this, while a wealthy family may not at all. The money given to a bail bondsman will not be given back, even if no charges are ever filed. The money bail system is unjust to poor people and the for-profit bail industry profits off of this. Most people in jail in the United States have not been convicted of a crime, but instead are in jail because they could not afford to pay cash bail. This does not only make money for the for-profit bail industry, but all the companies that profit off of keeping jails and prisons full such as those that make the clothes and food profit from the money bail system as well. The cost of all this? --the livelihoods and ability to care for their families of those incarcerated and the billions the United States spends to keep these people incarcerated. [[stock]] [[elements]] [[leverage points]] [[feedback loop]] [[resilience]] [[hierarchy]] [[authorship]] [[Main Menu]] The stock in this system is based on the actual function of the money bail system (keeping jails and prisons full) rather than the original intent of the money bail system when it was first designed (making sure people show up to court). Therefore, the stock is people in jail. Most people in jail have not been convicted of a crime. They are in jail awaiting trial because they could not afford to pay the bail amount set for their release. (The median bail amount for felonies is $10,000, which is 8 months income for the average person in jail because they could not afford bail). [[elements]] [[leverage points]] [[feedback loop]] [[resilience]] [[hierarchy]] [[authorship]] [[purpose]] [[Main Menu]] The elements of this system are people arrested, jails, judges, courthouses, money, bail bondsmen, the law / statute / federal rules of criminal procedure, police (arresting officers), lawyers, families, wealth, jobs (people may lose their jobs if they have to stay in jail, and then they can no longer pay court fees etc), and investors in bail bonds companies. [[stock]] [[leverage points]] [[feedback loop]] [[resilience]] [[hierarchy]] [[authorship]] [[purpose]] [[Main Menu]] The leverage points are: how much money someone and their family has, if their family can afford to pay bail, if their family can afford to pay a bail bondsman fee, if they are able to leave jail and return home and return to work, if they can afford to stay in jail for a long time and miss out on wages and caring for their families, if they can afford a lawyer, the amount their bail is placed at. Impactful leverage points include taking into account the situation of each individual person when setting bail, abolishing cash bail all together, replacing money bail with systems, breaking up the massive for-profit bail bond industry, community funds to bail out community members, legal assistance to those incarcerated because they couldn't afford bail, house-arrest, text reminders of court dates, decriminalizing minor infractions, legislation to protect those with mental illness from arrest, legislation to protect people from being arrested for not having a house, eliminating bail for nonviolent offenses, setting a cap on bail for nonviolent offenses, and requiring judges to take each individual's financial situation into account when setting bail. In creating an effective intervention in the form of bail reform, it is important that judges do not rely too much on "risk assessment tools'' as these reflect bias on the basis of race, class, and gender. Any reform that allows judges to deny release on the basis of the "risk" of that person is likely to allow judges to make biased decisions. For this reason, allowing too high levels of judicial discretion is dangerous. Judges may continue to set too-high bail if given too much discretion. Bail reform should also not replace pre-trial detention with too much supervision as this may have negative impacts to individuals communities and careers (restricting the freedom of these individuals who have not been convicted of a crime.) It is also important that useful data is collected and shared publicly so communities can see the positive impact of bail reform and so misinformation is easily disproved. The arrested individual should also be given the right to an attorney during the bail hearing. Finally, they should be given text and email reminders of court dates. [[stock]] [[elements]] [[feedback loop]] [[resilience]] [[hierarchy]] [[authorship]] [[purpose]] [[Main Menu]] The money bail system is part of a larger feedback loop that works with over-policing to keep poor people poor. That is, poor areas are overpoliced and so people living in these areas are more likely to be arrested. Whether or not they are guilty or even ever charged, those that are arrested will have to either pay bail bondsman fee or pay money bail if they do not want to stay in jail for a long time (and likely lose their job and not be able to care for their families etc). Staying in jail or paying these fees will have much more damaging effects on poor families, making them even more poor. This feedback loop continues because poor communities are over-policed, and it continues. [[stock]] [[elements]] [[leverage points]] [[resilience]] [[hierarchy]] [[authorship]] [[purpose]] [[Main Menu]] As bail bonds companies and their investors make more money off of this system, they grow in power and resources. As their power and resources grow, they are able to further lobby politicians to keep the money bail system the status quo, despite that it is unjust. This is the reason for the resilience of the money bail system, despite increasing public awareness and outrage about the injustice of this system. [[stock]] [[elements]] [[leverage points]] [[feedback loop]] [[hierarchy]] [[authorship]] [[purpose]] [[Main Menu]] The hierarchy is that the money bail system is a sub-system that plays a key role in the larger incarceration system in the United States of America, as it is responsible for a continually increasing number of people incarcerated in the United States of America, overcrowding jails and costing the country more and more money to keep them there. [[stock]] [[elements]] [[leverage points]] [[feedback loop]] [[resilience]] [[authorship]] [[purpose]] [[Main Menu]] The money bail system creates a system where wealthier people are less likely to be incarcerated before trial than someone who is poorer and accused of the same crime. This system not only perpetuates inequality, but also contributes to that the incarceration rate and number of people in prison has climbed dramatically since the war on drugs, even though the rate of crime has been declining. Housing the ~500,000 people who are incarcerated pre-trial because they can not afford bail costs the United States $9 billion per year. Most of these people were accused of minor, nonviolent offenses. So, if the money bail system is unjust and expensive for the United States, why does it continue? Lock-in is the phenomenon in which changing a specific software design is difficult because many other programs were designed to be dependent on it. While the money bail system is not technical, this phenomenon is still relevant. The money bail system is difficult to change because there are many independent groups with their own economic incentives to keep jails and prisons full. These systems have historical roots. After slavery was abolished, southern states did not want to lose their free labor. So, they criminalized minor offenses in order to arrest those who had been freed so that they could be forced to work when they could not pay the fines for being arrested. This led to convict leasing, a system of forced labor to provide prisoner labor to private parties. While convict leasing as in the post-slavery era does not exist today, incarcerated Americans still make goods for American companies and get paid nearly nothing for their labor. There are also still private parties with incentive to lobby politicians to criminalize minor offenses beyond the many corporations that benefit from prisoner labor including private prison contractors, and those that sell clothes, food, and other equipment to jails and prisons. In thinking about the future of the money bail system, flexibility is crucial for judges to be able to consider every person and their family’s situation individually. While locked-in guidelines for bail amounts based on what they are accused of could prevent bias on the basis of race or gender, it would prevent the judge from setting a lower amount for poorer individuals or for those who are clearly not a flight risk and are needed at home by their families. A better way to change the system would be to move away from money bail altogether, because as long as there are very rich people and very poor people in America, determining whether or not someone is detained pretrial based on how much money they can spend on bail, will never be fair. Rules should exist that prevent bias and unfairness on the basis of race, class, gender, and sexuality. However, rules should still allow judges flexibility based on individual situations. The masses should have an opportunity to impact policy more (not less) than lobbyists employed by comparatively smaller private parties with economic interests. Community bail funds are an example of the masses intervening, however the community should have the opportunity to advocate for bail reforms as the masses see fit, rather than those who profit off of the system. Typically, they will only set a certain amount of orders to be available, and only do it usually a few hours before closing. <img src="https://www.touchbistro.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/kitchen-order-system-inset-2.jpg" width="770" height="434"> With all those orders coming in all at once, there must be some kind of [[bug]] to pop up eventually... * Strategies in authorship methods for [[Effective workflow of architects]] by Kyungho Lee * [[ToGoodToGo]] by Jonathan Marcos * Finding [[informal housing]] in Lagos, Nigeria by Elizabeth Ogusanya * [[The Money Bail System in the United States of America]] by Elizabeth Singer The key to running architecture project successfully (in terms of workflow) is to choose a design atelier with an appropriate Authorship method for the scale of your project. If the scale of your project is small, working with an atelier with singular authorship should be fine. However, clients may have less authorship in design with singular authorship ateliers. [[Singular Authorship (Head Architect)]] [[Collective Authorship (Design Team)]] [[Collective Authorship (Design Team + Clients)]]Singular Authorship only works when the size of the atelier is very small. You should consider how to distribute singular authorship as the atelier grows in its size. Clients choose ateliers based on the head architect’s [[design principles]]. Since clients already have a very specific expectation on design identity, failing to deliver coherent design identity in initial proposals can be a deal breaker. Ways to communicate and govern [[design principles]] follow authorship philosophy. So choosing the right authorship method is the key for successful architecture project. Here are some [[tips]] with examples on using authorship and 'lock in' in a smart way. There are many stakeholders in architecture project such as clients, design team, head architect, builders, and government officials. Here I will focus on the three stakeholders (clients, designers, and a head architect) and talk about how authorship methods of the system affects design communication between them in the early design phase. width="800"> Which Authorship do you prefer? [[Singular Authorship (Head Architect)]] [[Collective Authorship (Design Team)]] [[Collective Authorship (Design Team + Clients)]]Ateliers often have hard time in increasing their business scale, because it is hard to train their designers with the firm’s design principles. Since those underlying rules regarding level of complexities in design language is hard to convey through words, miscommunication between a design principal and workers happen frequently. The design team may think their opinions on design principle is not reflected enough. Also head architects will have a hard time to convey design principles to many project designers. Currently design communication between clients and a design team takes a long process. First a design team has to present design options to the clients and wait for their feedback and usually those design feedback from clients are in verbal form. So lots of miscommunication happen when translating verbal language to visual langauge and vice verca. If there is a [[client-inclusive digital design tool]] where clients can quickly show their design feedback in visual language, the workflow of early design phase would be more effective. In terms of work-flow high fidelity in schematic design phase slows down the entire process so using tools that lock in designers under low-fidelity tool such as quick sketches or diagrams can be helpful. However low fidelity in initial proposals often affects the budget of the project, since the client decides whether they are willing to pay for the project based on initial proposals. So there is a trade-off between the effectiveness of workflow for architects and the clients’ satisfaction in design quality of initial proposals. [[Generative AI tool]] such DALL-E or Veras can come in handy in this case, because they are able to produce extremely realistic renderings in the very early stage. While [[Generative AI tool]] can be helpful for pursuing Collective Authorship throughout the design team, building such tool is quite hard. Generative AI tool for the design team should provide a lot more control in design than the design tools for clients with little 'lock in'.You have been [[arrested.]]You go to jail, joining others in jail who have been arrested. Do you have $30,000 to put up for bail or do you know anyone that is willing to? [[Yes]] [[No]]You may pay $30,000 for bail and get it back if you show up to court on your court date. You may leave jail and go home.Do you want to call a bail bondsman? They can put up your bail for you but you have to pay them $3000 that you will never get back. Do you have $3000 in exact change you can spend on this? [[Call bail bondsman]] [[No thank you]] You may pay $3,000 to the bailbondsman and you will not get it back. You may leave jail and go home.Since you or a bailbondsman have not put up bail, you must stay in jail. Eventually, you will get a chance to [[see your attorney]].Can you afford an attorney, or do you need a public defender? [[call my lawyer]] [[please provide me with a public defender]]You may see your lawyer, who may be able to advocate for your right for a speedy trial. Otherwise, you must decide if you want to [[continue waiting in jail while you wait for your court date, which could take years]] [[or plead gulty and give up your right to a trial so you can take a deal now]].Your public defender is overworked, and does not have time to advocate for a speedy trial for your or any other legal assistance you might need. Your public defender does not have time to worry about if you are guilty. Your public defender has very little time to help you. The prosecuter knows this and offers you a deal: you may[[continue waiting in jail while you wait for your court date, which could take years]] [[or plead gulty and give up your right to a trial so you can take a deal now]]. (It's probably a bad deal.) Your public defender and the prosecuter will push you to do this because the courts do not actually have the ability to try most people in jail awaiting their court dates. There are too many people in jail and not enough time. This is the single greatest driver of convictions. Not guilt, but plea deals in order to avoid trial because the person in jail is forced to sit in jail for years waiting for a trial since they could not afford bail.You are going to continue to be detained pre-trial. You cannot go to work or go home to take care of your kids. You are in jail for however long it takes for you to get in front of a judge. This may take years. You have given up your right to a trial and will now serve your sentance.Architecture ateliers with design principles show a pattern in designing architecture. Adopting merely a particular set of materials or geometries does not lead to design identity. A strong design identity is found in underlying rules that govern the level of complexities ‘Entropy’ (a measure of disorder) in proportion, repetition, rhythm, variety and unity of design. Some architects prefer to keep their plan in order while pursuing visual complexities in section and others keep sections of architecture in order and achieve complexity through the mixed use of materials. We can break down design components of architecture into plan , section, elevation patterns, materials, colors and details. And every architect has different strategies in achieving level of complexity they want. They make decisions on which design component to keep simple and where to introduce chaos so that the design as a whole is in a balance in aesthetic complexities. The client-inclusive design tool takes advantage of the authorship tips from examples: [['Lock in' to lower the barriers to entry]] the tool is easy for clients to use by 'locking in' many design features. [[Deliberate Inconvenience that leads to more Authorship]]: the tool also intantly gives visual feedbacks as clients interact with it. Through deliberately designed inconvenience to get involved in design process, clients can have more design authorship. Clients can effectively convey design feedbacks through the tools. <img width="800"> There are laborious works that have less to do with authorship such as hatching patterns, erasing drawing repetitive stairs… etc. Rhino has great tools to finish these repetitive tasks a lot quicker than hand drafting. This kind of convenience enables architects spend more time on creative works. Also nurbs modeling in rhino makes it a lot easier to achieve curved surfaces. Projects that used Rhino as a tool tend to have more curved surfaces in their design. Nurbs modeling in Rhino provides a convenient way to create and manipulate curves so that users can focus on the design of their 3d model rather than putting efforts on making curves. <b>Deliberate Inconvenience that leads to more Authorship (Ikea)</b> <img src="https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod/images/766/articles/2016/12/tol-building-furniture-takes-relationship-1509124322.jpeg?resize=1200:*" width="800"> IKEA cleverly uses ‘inconvenience’, the hassle to assemble your furniture by yourself. After building their own furniture, customers usually have more emotional attachment and ownership to their furniture. This approach is valuable when building digital products using generative AI, because we often only focus on achieving more convenience.
